<p><b>Henry Louis "H. L." Mencken</b> (September 12, 1880 â€“ January 29, 1956), was an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Journalist" title="Journalist">journalist</a>, <a href="/wiki/Essay" title="Essay">essayist</a>, <a href="/wiki/Magazine" title="Magazine">magazine</a> <a href="/wiki/Editing" title="Editing">editor</a>, <a href="/wiki/Satire" title="Satire">satirist</a>, acerbic <a href="/wiki/Social_criticism" title="Social criticism">critic</a> of American <a href="/wiki/American_way" title="American way">life</a> and <a href="/wiki/Culture_of_the_United_States" title="Culture of the United States">culture</a>, and a student of <a href="/wiki/American_English" title="American English">American English</a>. Mencken, known as the "Sage of <a href="/wiki/Baltimore,_Maryland" title="Baltimore, Maryland" class="mw-redirect">Baltimore</a>", is regarded as one of the most influential American <a href="/wiki/Writer" title="Writer">writers</a> and <a href="/wiki/Prose" title="Prose">prose</a> <a href="/wiki/Stylistics_(linguistics)" title="Stylistics (linguistics)">stylists</a> of the first half of the 20th century.</p>
<p>Mencken is perhaps best remembered today for <i><a href="/wiki/The_American_Language" title="The American Language">The American Language</a></i>, a multi-volume study of how the English language is spoken in the United States, and for his satirical reporting on the <a href="/wiki/Scopes_trial" title="Scopes trial" class="mw-redirect">Scopes trial</a>, which he named the "Monkey" trial.</p>
